   234	| **Multi-company / multi-contact for billing** | Intermarket dealer transactions (KBM REQ-033) | **CRM (§3.02 D-4)** — relationship model locked; Financial Management uses the model for billing and payment |
   235	
   236	## 3.08.5 Recommendation summary
   237	
   238	The merged-company Financial Management playbook in shorthand:
   239	
   240	- **Foundation:** Single subsidiary, USD-only, 13-period calendar, merged-company COA designed from clean foundation using NetSuite dimensional fields
   241	- **Period close:** NetSuite Period Close Checklist with 7-day working target (Pivot's current cadence)
   242	- **Revenue recognition:** Joint design session for merged-company recognition rules with ASC 606 compliance validation; Pivot's accrued revenue journal-entry framework with approval workflow as operational mechanism
   243	- **Labor markup:** 15% markup eliminated; merged-company GP operates on actual labor cost per locked CRM §3.02 D-6 framework
   244	- **GP reporting:** Dual GP framework per Pivot's actual-vs-quoted model, with role-based visibility (sales sees commissionable GP, management sees actual GP)
   245	- **Banking:** Multi-bank capability; Advanced Electronic Bill Payments for ACH; Cash360 dashboard; positive pay configured per bank capabilities
   246	- **Expense management:** Joint platform evaluation (Expensify or RAMP); platform decision at working session
   247	- **Fixed assets:** NetSuite Fixed Asset module adopted; Bloomberg sunset
   248	- **Vendor credit limits:** KBM's custom alert workflow framework adopted (90% warning threshold)
   249	- **Collections / AR:** Pivot's collections management and AR framework adopted; KBM's customer-portal and finance-charge capabilities carry forward
   250	- **Tax management:** Native SuiteTax for nexus management (KBM's 48-state nexus + Pivot's California focus = merged-company nexus footprint)
   251	- **Reporting:** Real-time financial dashboards replacing Excel-based reporting; project-level KPI dashboards per locked BI §3.09 framework
   252	
   253	Net read: the merged-company Financial Management combines design choices that fit the merged-company's situation. Pivot's contributions reflect its operational maturity (7-day close, accrued revenue framework, dedicated collections and AR sub-areas, dual GP actual-vs-quoted, 16-section comprehensive coverage). KBM's contributions reflect its rigorous decision-discipline orientation (eight-session follow-up framework, three critical decision gates, named stakeholder roles, vendor credit-limit detail, banking-partner specificity). The merged company benefits from both — Pivot's process maturity becomes the operational baseline; KBM's decision discipline becomes the implementation rigor.
